Reigning national champions Ulinzi Warriors and Equity Bank extended their fine form in the Kenya Basketball Federation Premier League playoff semifinals at the Nyayo Stadium. Warriors are a win away from the finals after a 79-69 win over Strathmore University Blades in Game Two while Equity pipped Zetech University Sparks 66-58 to also put themselves in good stead for the finals. Warriors and Strathmore failed to hit the target in the opening two minutes before the students took the first quarter a 15-12 and were the better side at 22-15 at the break. An Eric Mutoro basket beat the buzzer for a 60-47 cushion as the third quarter wounded as the soldiers created an unassailable lead. “We lacked the mental toughness to sustain a lead after being in a control. It’s not over. Game Three is very important. We will regroup and plot for it,” said Blades' coach Tony Ochieng. In another semis, Equity Bank (men) get the better of Kenya Ports Authority (KPA) in a 78-66 scoreline for a  2-0 series lead. The bankers roared away to a 23-15 first-quarter margin but were pegged down 21-13 by the porters as both teams went to the break tied 36-36. The dockers sunk deep into problems trailing 65-50 at the start of the last quarter as Equity swiftly answered every punch thrown at them. Eric Ochieng tossed in 29 points while Davis Siaji made 18 for Equity. KPA’s Victor Odendo shot 16 and Lenox Wanje 13. “We played well against a team that has been in the finals for so many years. This is our first semis and we are progressing well. We will prepare well for the week ahead,” said the bankers' coach, Carey Oketch. KPA’s Sammy Kiki observed: “They punished us on the three points. We have to win the next game when we go to Mombasa.” In the women's action, Debbie Obunga's three-pointer sparked Zetech to a 5-0 lead but Equity responded with a 9-5 cushion and, a lead they took to the end of the quarter as 22-16. Melissa Akinyi's exploits saw Equity command a 26-23 halftime advantage. The last two quarters belonged to the students as they were on top 18-14 and 17-16. But the pressure didn’t last long. After closing in 38-40, Zetech took their feet off the gas as Equity sailed away 50-41 as the last stanza started. Akinyi tossed in 17 points and  Betty Kananu had another 12 for the victors. Sparks' Valerie Kemunto bagged game-high 22 and Obunga had 15. Equity Bank coach David Maina said: It’s a good win for us. Yesterday (Saturday) we had a lot of pressure. We were a bit composed today.” “I am happy we were in the lead from the word go. We never gave them a chance. It’s not over though. We still have one more game to go.” In the other semis, Kenya Ports Authority (KPA) hammered  Storms 89-61 to also move up 2-0 in the series. The porters sailed away for a 25-12 first-quarter advantage before Storms changed the tide, taking the second 22-19. It was the same story in the third with KPA racing away to a 28-16 edge before taking the fourth with a 17-11 margin. Natalie Akinyi led KPA's rout with 21 points and Vilma Achieng tallied 17. Jemima Knight hit 18 for the losers. “As far as I am concerned the series is over. Let them come to Mombasa but they should know we will close all doors,” a confident KPA coach stated. In a lower division match, Africa Nazarene University (ANU) also went 2-0 after a high-scoring 87-84 victory.